revision.text:
'''Abortion in Vanuatu''' is severely restricted by criminal law.<ref name=UN>{{cite book|title=Abortion Policies: Oman to Zimbabwe|date=2001|publisher=United Nations Publications|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3iNmQIP7S2AC&dq=abortion+in+vanuatu&source=gbs_navlinks_s|accessdate=23 November 2014}}</ref> Abortion is illegal under the provisions of section 117 of the Vanuatu Penal Code, Act No. 17 or 7 August 1981.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vanuatu.usp.ac.fj/library/online/Pacific_law/Murgatroyd3.htm|title=Abortion Policies: a review of policies, legislation and social indicators for the South Pacific|website=www.vanuatu.usp.ac.fj|access-date=2018-09-19}}</ref> The code states that any women who intentionally induces a miscarriage is subject to up to two years' imprisonment.<ref name="UN" /> Abortion is illegal in cases of [[rape]], [[incest]], and threats to fetal health.<ref name=abc>{{cite news|last1=Graue|first1=Catherine|title=New study to research Vanuatu's illegal abortions with fears rates are increasing|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-06-21/vanuatu-health-workers-worried-about-increasing-abortion-rat/5533848|accessdate=23 November 2014|work=ABC News|date=20 June 2014}}</ref> The only allocations for abortion are to save the life or the pregnant women and to preserve physical and mental health.{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}} Under section 113 of the code the legal abortion must be done before the 28th week of pregnancy.{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}}

== Self-induced abortions ==
The Vanuatu Family Health Association reports various methods women use for [[self-induced abortion]]s, including the use of local leaves or bark from a tree.<ref name=abc /> Abortions like this that are outside of the medical system endanger the lives of women, as even an immediate visit to a nearby hospital or clinic may be futile if that medical facility does not have the equipment to repair any damage.<ref name=abc />

