{{For|the Canadian comedy band|Zimmers Hole}} {{Use British English|date=October 2012}} {{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}} {{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians --> | name = The Zimmers | image = | caption = | image_size = | background = group_or_band | origin = United Kingdom | instrument = | genre = [[Rock music|Rock]] | label = unsigned | years_active = 2007–present | website = [http://www.thezimmers.co.uk Official website] | current_members = See [[#Members|Members]] }}
'''The Zimmers''' are an English band formed in 2007 and are thought to have the oldest members of any group in the world.<ref>{{cite news|title=Power To The People: The Great Granny Chart Invasion|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/power_to_the_people/6615695.stm|accessdate=2007-05-28|work=[[BBC News]]|date=2 May 2007}}</ref> The oldest member, [[Buster Martin]], claimed to have been born in 1906, although some sources indicate he was born in 1913. Martin died in 2011. Former lead singer Alf Carretta died on 29 June 2010, aged 93.<ref>{{cite news|title=British geriatrics take to the rock star life|last=Baker|first=Luke|date=30 May 2007|publisher=Reuters}}</ref> The group takes its name from the [[Walker (mobility)|Zimmer frame]], the UK term for a mobility aid known in other countries as a [[Walker (mobility)|walker]].
The band was created as a feature in a [[BBC Television]] documentary which aired on 28 May 2007.<ref name="elders">{{cite news|title=Rock elders aim for chart success|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/6549333.stm|accessdate=2007-04-18|work=[[BBC News]]|date=13 April 2007}}</ref> The feature of forming the band and recording a single was intended to give a voice to the feelings of isolation and imprisonment suffered by the elderly. The Zimmers' logo is a parody of [[The Beatles]]' logo, as is the image of them walking across [[Abbey Road (street)|Abbey Road]].
On 7 April 2012, the band performed the [[Beastie Boys]]' "[[(You Gotta) Fight for Your Right (To Party!)]]" on ''[[Britain's Got Talent (series 6)|Britain's Got Talent]]''. The band toured in 2013, performing in Warrington on 25 May that year.
==Discography== The Zimmers released their first single, a [[Cover version|cover]] of [[The Who|The Who's]] "[[My Generation (The Who song)|My Generation]]", reaching #26 in the [[UK Singles Chart]], on 28 May 2007. The song was produced by [[Mike Hedges]], the [[music video|video]] shot by Geoff Wonfor, and it was recorded in the Beatles Studio 2 at [[Abbey Road Studios|Abbey Road]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Talkin' 'bout OUR generation|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/pages/live/articles/showbiz/showbiznews.html?in_article_id=448045&in_page_id=1773|publisher=[[Daily Mail]]|accessdate = 2016-07-30| location=London | date=12 April 2007}}</ref>
On during the 13 July 2007 broadcast of the ''[[Richard & Judy]]'' show, The Zimmers announced their cover of [[The Prodigy]]'s "[[Firestarter (The Prodigy song)|Firestarter]]".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/magazine/7661275.stm|title=What The Zimmers did next|date=9 October 2008|accessdate=2008-10-10|publisher=[[BBC.co.uk]]|last=Samuels|first=Tim}}</ref> In September 2008, the band released their first full-length album ''Lust for Life'', which featured versions of songs by [[Eric Clapton]], [[The Beatles]] and [[Frank Sinatra]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.meeja.com.au/index.php?display_article_id=254|title=Geriatric rockers live long enough to release long-play |publisher=Meeja.com.au|date=23 September 2008|accessdate=2008-09-23}}</ref>
==BBC documentary== Documentary-maker [[Tim Samuels]] travelled Britain, investigating the feelings of isolation and imprisonment suffered by the country's elderly, as part of the BBC's ''Power to the People'' series.<ref>{{cite news|title=Power to the People – a three-part series of mischievous documentaries|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/power_to_the_people/about_the_series/default.stm|accessdate=2007-05-29|work=[[BBC News]]|date=8 May 2007}}</ref> Samuels recruits pensioners otherwise stuck in institutions and [[towerblock]]s, and they air their grievances, culminating in the recording of the group's first single, where the group ''"sticks it back to the society that has cast them aside"''.<ref name="elders" />
==''Britain's Got Talent''== 15 members of the band, aged 66 to 88, appeared on ''[[Britain's Got Talent]]'' on 7 April 2012, performing the [[Beastie Boys]]' track "[[(You Gotta) Fight for Your Right (To Party!)]]".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-18017349 |title=Beastie Boys return to US top 20 - BBC News |website=Bbc.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2016-12-23}}</ref> They walked on stage with thick coats and anoraks. Their oldest member, 88-year-old Grace Cooke, started the audition by singing a slow version of "[[What the World Needs Now Is Love|What the World Needs Now]]". They all then removed their coats, revealing ostentatious jewellery (described as 'bling' by one the judges) and hoodies and began to sing the Beasties track.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://programmes.stv.tv/britains-got-talent/latest/302964-britains-got-talent-oap-group-the-zimmers-fight-for-their-right-to-party/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-05-16 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120411205345/http://programmes.stv.tv/britains-got-talent/latest/302964-britains-got-talent-oap-group-the-zimmers-fight-for-their-right-to-party/ |archivedate=11 April 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> They received four yes votes and survived through the live semi-finals.
In the semi-finals The Zimmers again performed a pop song; [[LMFAO (group)|LMFAO]]'s "[[Sexy and I Know It]]". They did not get to the finals.
